Your problem is that the accessor method [`JObject.Item Property (String)`](https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/P_Newtonsoft_Json_Linq_JObject_Item_1.htm), used in `Parent[&quot;rules&quot;].Add(sampleObj)`, returns a [`JToken`](https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/T_Newtonsoft_Json_Linq_JToken.htm), which is the abstract base class for all possible JSON values -- primitive or non-primitive.  As such it has no `Add()` method, because the derived class [`JValue`](https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/T_Newtonsoft_Json_Linq_JValue.htm) representing a primitive value has no `Add()` method.

Thus you will need to cast `Parent[&quot;rules&quot;]` to its actual type, which is [`JArray`](https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/T_Newtonsoft_Json_Linq_JArray.htm), in order to add an array item:

    ((JArray)Parent[&quot;rules&quot;]).Add(sampleObj);

If you think it looks cleaner, you can use [`JToken.Value&lt;T&gt;(Object key)`](https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/M_Newtonsoft_Json_Linq_JToken_Value__1.htm) instead of an inline cast, which does the same thing:

	Parent.Value&lt;JArray&gt;(&quot;rules&quot;).Add(sampleObj);
    
Or, if there&#39;s a chance that the `&quot;rules&quot;` array hasn&#39;t been created yet:

	var array = Parent.Value&lt;JArray&gt;(&quot;rules&quot;) ?? (JArray)(Parent[&quot;rules&quot;] = new JArray());
	array.Add(sampleObj);
			
Similarly, [`JToken.SelectToken Method (String)`](https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/M_Newtonsoft_Json_Linq_JToken_SelectToken.htm) returns a `JToken` and so casting is also required.

Related:

 - *[JSON.NET: Why Use JToken--ever?](https://stackoverflow.com/a/38212978/3744182)*.
 - *[JContainer, JObject, JToken and Linq confusion](https://stackoverflow.com/a/38560188/3744182)*.

Demo fiddle [here](https://dotnetfiddle.net/wTppEI).

